Root tree constraints are the answer to 'how do agents find project principles?'

Pattern: write constraints on '.' (root tree). context walks parent dirs
up to root, so every file inherits them. After commits, the root tree OID
changes and the note becomes stale — but stale-tree scanning (new in this
commit) finds it via targets-treepath edge. find constraint also works.

This commit also fixed resolve_target for '.' — it was broken because
git rev-parse HEAD:. fails (need HEAD^{tree} instead).

The 7 principles are now a living note. They'll go stale after the next
commit but stay visible. When we want to update them, we write a new
note on the new root tree and the old one auto-supersedes.
